### Companion Objects in Kotlin

Companion objects are special object declarations inside a class, allowing static-like members that are tied to the class rather than instances.

---

### Basic Companion Object

```kotlin
class MyClass {
    companion object {
        val TAG = "MyClass"
        fun create(): MyClass = MyClass()
    }
}

fun main() {
    println(MyClass.TAG)       // Access like static field
    val obj = MyClass.create() // Access like static method
}
```

---

### Named Companion Objects

Companion objects can have names. If unnamed, the default name is `Companion`.

```kotlin
class MyClass {
    companion object Factory {
        fun create(): MyClass = MyClass()
    }
}

// Access via name or omit
MyClass.Factory.create()
MyClass.create()  // Also works
```

---

### Implementing Interfaces

Companion objects can implement interfaces.

```kotlin
interface JsonFactory<T> {
    fun fromJson(json: String): T
}

data class User(val name: String, val age: Int) {
    companion object : JsonFactory<User> {
        override fun fromJson(json: String): User {
            // Parse JSON logic
            return User("Alice", 30)
        }
    }
}
```

---

### Extensions on Companion Objects

```kotlin
class MyClass {
    companion object {}
}

fun MyClass.Companion.hello() = "Hello from companion!"

fun main() {
    println(MyClass.hello())  // Hello from companion!
}
```

---

### Companion Object vs Java Static

| Kotlin Companion Object | Java Static |
|------------------------|-------------|
| Can have a name | No name |
| Can implement interfaces | Cannot implement interfaces |
| Can be extended | Cannot be extended |
| Is an actual object (singleton) | Not an object |

---

### Using @JvmStatic

For Java interop, use `@JvmStatic` to expose members as true static methods/fields.

```kotlin
class MyClass {
    companion object {
        @JvmStatic
        fun staticMethod() = println("Called as static")

        @JvmField
        val CONSTANT = 42
    }
}
```

> **Key Point:** Companion objects are true singleton objects inside a class. They provide a home for factory methods, constants, and static-like behavior.

codeExample:
class Database private constructor(val name: String) {
    companion object {
        private val instances = mutableMapOf<String, Database>()

        fun getInstance(name: String): Database {
            return instances.getOrPut(name) { Database(name) }
        }
    }

    fun query(sql: String) {
        println("$name: executing $sql")
    }
}

fun main() {
    val db1 = Database.getInstance("mydb")
    val db2 = Database.getInstance("mydb")
    println(db1 === db2)  // true (same instance)
    db1.query("SELECT * FROM users")
}
